{{Infobox artwork |image_file=Giovanni Paolo Panini – Ancient Rome.jpg |title=Ancient Rome |artist= Giovanni Paolo Panini |year=1757 |medium=[[Oil painting|Oil on canvas]] |height_metric=172.1 |width_metric=229.9 |height_imperial=67.75 |width_imperial=90.5 |metric_unit=cm |imperial_unit=in |city=[[New York City|New York]] |museum=[[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] }} '''''Ancient Rome''''' is an [[Oil painting|oil on canvas]] painting by [[Giovanni Paolo Panini]]. It is owned by and on display at the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] in [[New York City]]. Panini painted the piece as a [[pendant painting]] to ''[[Modern Rome]]'' for the [[Étienne François, duc de Choiseul|Count de Stainville]] in 1757.<ref name="Met">"[http://www.metmuseum.org/toah/hd/frac/ho_52.63.2.htm Giovanni Paolo Panini: Modern Rome (52.63.2)]". In Heilbrunn Timeline of Art History. New York: The Metropolitan Museum of Art, 2000–. (October 2006). Retrieved November 28, 2009.</ref> The painting depicts many of the most significant architectural sites and sculptures from [[Ancient Rome]], such as the [[Colosseum]], the [[Pantheon, Rome|Pantheon]], ''[[Laocoön and His Sons]]'', and ''[[Farnese Hercules]]''.<ref name="USAD">{{cite book |title=Art Resource Guide: 18th Century and Early 19th-Century French Art |page=25 |year= 2009| publisher=[[United States Academic Decathlon]]}}</ref> Both Panini and Panini's patron the Count de Stainville make an appearance in the work. Panini sits in the armchair and the Count de Stainville stands holding a guidebook.<ref name="Met" /><ref name="USAD" />
